Ooh my goodness! Yes this place is truly a Michelin Starr restaurant. The food and drink like no other. Someone had mention how pricy it was, I'm a true believer you get what you pay for. Every plate was over the top in taste and in presentation. Paired with the recommended glass of wine, it was truly a culinary delight. I get why there is a three month waiting list.

After emailing the manager, I get a call back from their guest service manager, Steven, to follow up on my review and to see if they can compensate the disappointing experience we had to my satisfaction. He apologized and explained how their system works and that the captain has been notified and spoken to by the GM and boss. Also he said there was a miscommunication in making the reservation...that my husband did not mention it was a celebration for our marriage ceremony. Regardless an anniversary, wedding, birthday or just a night to dine in one of the highly rated restaurants in SF, service should not differ based on the occassion. Honestly, I expected them to invite us back to makeup for ruinning our special night but instead he just apologized many times. He then offered to refund the tip we left and said we should not tip if service did not satisfy us. Well, thanks Gary Danko for the bad experience. This is my first and will be my last to dine in.

We have been there four times. After the first three times, this was certainly a 5 star restaurant in my mind. Danko's was on our list to visit every year on our way to our annual Napa trip. That was of course, until our last meal there. After that, this restaurant continues to deserve a 5 star rating, but the odds of us ever returning any time soon are slim. The first three visits were, simply stated, magical. After our first visit, we could not stop talking about this place. From the way they greet you at the door, to how promptly they show you to your table, to the magically orchestrated waiting staff, to the reliable and timely serving style of this restaurant, to the magical cheese cart and service, to the perfect food execution, to the two members of the restaurant waiting at the door with our jackets in hand waiting to assist us in putting them on, to a cab waiting for us at the door. This place is, simply, magical!!! This restaurant appears to have multiple waiters per guess... not per table, per guests!!! Simply amazing. So décor, ambiance, food, cheese cart, and service is, basically, perfection. If you haven't, you must go!!!!! We have sent so many friends Danko's way and they all came back raving about this place. We usually opt for the 4 course menu. My wife likes her cheese so she either adds the cheese course or makes one of her 4 courses the cheese course. Also, and of some importance, is that Danko's doesn't care if you want your 4 courses to be 4 desserts... or 4 appetizers. They are very flexible in this department and that's a nice touch. Finally, Danko's has a $40 corkage fee so taking your own wine makes some sense although they do have some vey reasonably priced wines on their list, like Antica for $110 ($54 retail); Groth for $131 ($65 retail); and some very nice Pinots in the $100 range. (PS: complete Wine List is on line!) So, with every visit, this restaurant delivered and delivered again. Until the last visit that is. I am not going to get into it because I think this is an amazing restaurant worthy of its 5 star rating and one idiotic comment by the waiter should not taint what has otherwise been a great experience time and time again.

Gary Danko lived up to every expectation I had for it. Make reservations as early as possible - I made reservations for two on a Friday as soon as reservations opened for that day and was only able to get 5:30p. If you drive here, count on valet; parking is pretty much impossible. We arrived and were seated immediately and enjoyed impeccable service throughout the night. Attentive yet respectful and not at all obtrusive. Bread is served throughout your dinner; they try to make sure you have a piece on your plate at all times. The amuse bouche was a gazpacho that was a concentrated punch of flavor. Each course came out promptly without much wait in between. We ordered: Crispy Farm Egg - an absolute must for anyone that comes to GD. An amazing and decadent dish with fantastic flavor and texture. Totally unique. Corn Soup w Crab - this is the only course that was just "good." It tasted great, it just seemed recreate-able. Scallops - amazing texture. So tender... They seemed sous vide. Roast Lobster - classic dish done fantastically. Essentially this is lobster and mash, but the lobster is buttery perfection and everything is just done so well. Branzini - this is a must for fish fans. The dish itself is stunning, then the pieces of fish have a perfect crispy seat on the skin side. Filet of Beef - did not try this but got great feedback! Moroccan Squab - I was surprised by how big this portion was. Definitely the size of a regular entree at other restaurants. Don't be scared by how rare the meat seems... It is so, so good. The flavors are amazing on this dish; the raisins and almonds all work together beautifully. Ended the meal with a complimentary birthday dessert (chocolate mousse cake and assorted cookies) which were really delicious, and took a their gift of a small pineapple cream cheese cake home. (Tasted great the next day). Unfortunately we had a bad experience at the end of the night with our car taking half an hour to appear from valet, but it was a great dinner overall. Take your time at GD... Don't rush it and enjoy every bite!

If only I could give 6 stars--I cannot heap enough superlatives onto this place, which we've been to many times over more than a decade, and we adore. They remain remarkably consistent. The caviar service is insane, with the blini and creme fraiche, chives. Every single item on their menu rocks, it's impossible to choose badly. My husband loves their Coconut Thai curry and I love their horseradish crusted salmon. Their branzini, lamb loin, pork, and quail are all the total bomb. I pretty much live and die by their cheese cart, which I think is the absolute hands down the freakin BEST in the city. That rolling cart comes my way and I wanna shout at the top of my lungs, "Push that cheese into my face! :-)" Seriously, folks, for all you cheese lovers out there, get thee to your awaiting mecca. These people take their cheese seriously. I'm so over people taking cheese straight out of the refrigerator, and hurling a soft ripened brillat savarin or epoisse or brie at me. Is it a hockey puck or meant to be oozing butter like onto bread? The restaurant inevitably gives me a song and dance about some "city health ordinance" requiring them to refrigerate their cheese. I'd go to Gary Danko for their cheese course alone, an unforgettable experience and education in its own right. The variety of cheese is ridiculous--sheep, goat, cow . . . it's all there. Soft and creamy to hard--young and fresh to aged years. Tell them what you like and don't, they customize everything, and here's the best part: they engage in conversation with you about this process, e.g. I told them I need to avoid everything aged beyond 9 months (due to allergy), which they carefully selected out of. The desserts, my gosh it's a paradise for my husband with the sweet tooth that doesn't not quit. You souffle lovers out there, make a run for G.D.--each souffle is divine. As if the desset isn't enough, they'll close out the dinner with a little tray of sweet bites: mignardises. And as we're waddling out he door, they press a beautifully wrapped in gold paper gift into our hands; it's been a mini muffin or fresh bread or more sweets :-) The customer service is one of the best in the world. They actually give a damn, and want to please you, want to make you happy. This is not just a "job" for them. It's a career, which they take pride in, and clearly went to a hell of a training for. It's like stepping into a time warp of yesteryear--the service is everything: genteel, old world, courtly, kind and caring; every single person from start to finish, from being greeted to bidding farewell, they are individually and collectively masterful at makes us feel cared for. I wouldn't be surprised if they went to four years of hospitality school :-) Yes, G.D. cooks and serve superlative food but this is secondary to their main job: they make us feel loved.

Even if you're a prole like me you'll enjoy the food. Went here for an intimate dinner for a friend's birthday and I had absolutely zero complaints. I would definitely come here again. Ate: 4-courser with wine

After a full day of early drinking and "running" for Bay to Breakers 2012, the only obvious choice for dinner before my flight home was to eat at Gary Danko. It was already a day of excess so why not add more excess, in the form or foie gras, to dinner as well. Did not have reservation but arrived shortly after they opened to grab at seat at the bar. In a way, bar seating is actually better because unlike the regular tables, you aren't forced to choose a 3-4-5 course meal, you can go a la carte. I went for the 3 course and each was just as heavenly as the next. Started off with an amuse of carrot soup. I never really liked cooked carrots but the flavors in this soup was so much more. First course was the foie gras. It was sitting on a bed of caramelized onions, I think. With a small mache salad on the side. Melt in my mouth goodness! This was no small piece that left you wanting more, I think it was the size of a small steak! I'm glad I was able to stuff myself with such a delicious and large amount of foie before the stupid ban takes place. Second got the branzini. The crust was super crispy without the rest of the fish being too dry either. It was sitting on a puree, which I can't remember what it was. Although it was good, this was probably my least favorite dish of the three I got. Nothing against it, but I'm just partial to my fobby style steamed fish. You can take the girl out of China, but not the China out of the girl I guess. Last course for me was the duck breast on duck confit hash. Let's talk about this hash first. It was more like a ball of crispy duck confit with a speckle of potatoes in it, that's how generous they are with the duck in this hash. The duck breast was medium and tender and perfect compliment to eat with the hash. This dish was just as generous in their portions too! I've been to Michelin star places leaving hungry after a 5 course meal, but halfway through the duck all the rich food was settling in. This is a place where you get both quality and quantity. My friends ordered dessert so I got to try both the Chocolate souffle and the butter cake. The souffle was light as air, but I felt like it needed to be drenched with more chocolate, it's just my preference for anything chocolate to be thick rich and decadent. The butter cake was all that and more. One bite and you can taste the butter, apple, spices all melt and meld in your mouth. Top that with the vanilla ice cream on the side and it was a perfect end to the meal. I wish I lived closer because I would definitely come back, four courses next time! =)

Californian cusine in SF is definitely a game that you're a part of whether you knew it or not. The players are the range of restaurants who invite you to sit and experience how they each choose to play the game. If in the end you find yourself a used and abused fan, they ask you to not hate the player but yes, hate the game. On the surface, Californian cuisine is all about fusion. Echoing the state's progressive public policies, it means integrating disparate elements and techniques to harness the best each has to offer. This results in a compelling platform or presentation and wow, are Californian cusine dishes compelling. Pretty, so pretty. But drilling down on these tanatlizing presentations, you'll find that while the common accenting of dishes with avocado, figs, persimmons and such provide for an air of healthy freshness, the game is played at a much deeper level. Like in politics, it's ultimately all about the rich, and Californian cuisine is deceptively rich. For example, don't be surprised if there's a full cup of creme (fresh, of course, however) in that small bowl of butternut squash soup. So when they're wheeling your ass out in a butter coma whith a smile on your face, you'll at least know why. These are the masters of the game. I enjoy being duped by these all-stars every time and I think you will, too. I was so ready to bring the hate for this place but they totally won me over. One of the premiere SF restaurants that actually push beyond my cynical appraisal of the genre. Everything was 5 stars: food, service, and ambience.

Gary Danko...what can I say that hasn't already been said? After waiting over 2 years, I finally found an occasion to dine here. I decided to have my birthday celebration here. For a special occasion, this is the perfect place to go to. I really felt special on my birthday. The food is a feast for all the senses. The presentation is simply beautiful. The service is top notch but unpretentious. And of course, the food is absolutely fantastic. Really, there's not much I can say that hasn't been said already. It's Gary Danko. Enough said. 5 stars.

    10/13/2014

    Gary Danko lived up to every expectation I had for it. Make reservations as early as possible - I made reservations for two on a Friday as soon as reservations opened for that day and was only able to get 5:30p. If you drive here, count on valet; parking is pretty much impossible. We arrived and were seated immediately and enjoyed impeccable service throughout the night. Attentive yet respectful and not at all obtrusive. Bread is served throughout your dinner; they try to make sure you have a piece on your plate at all times. The amuse bouche was a gazpacho that was a concentrated punch of flavor. Each course came out promptly without much wait in between.

    We ordered:
    Crispy Farm Egg - an absolute must for anyone that comes to GD. An amazing and decadent dish with fantastic flavor and texture. Totally unique.
    Corn Soup w Crab - this is the only course that was just "good." It tasted great, it just seemed recreate-able.
    Scallops - amazing texture. So tender... They seemed sous vide.
    Roast Lobster - classic dish done fantastically. Essentially this is lobster and mash, but the lobster is buttery perfection and everything is just done so well.
    Branzini - this is a must for fish fans. The dish itself is stunning, then the pieces of fish have a perfect crispy seat on the skin side.
    Filet of Beef - did not try this but got great feedback!
    Moroccan Squab - I was surprised by how big this portion was. Definitely the size of a regular entree at other restaurants. Don't be scared by how rare the meat seems... It is so, so good. The flavors are amazing on this dish; the raisins and almonds all work together beautifully.

    Ended the meal with a complimentary birthday dessert (chocolate mousse cake and assorted cookies) which were really delicious, and took a their gift of a small pineapple cream cheese cake home. (Tasted great the next day).

    Unfortunately we had a bad experience at the end of the night with our car taking half an hour to appear from valet, but it was a great dinner overall. Take your time at GD... Don't rush it and enjoy every bite!

    7/2/2017

    If only I could give 6 stars--I cannot heap enough superlatives onto this place, which we've been to many times over more than a decade, and we adore. They remain remarkably consistent. The caviar service is insane, with the blini and creme fraiche, chives. Every single item on their menu rocks, it's impossible to choose badly. My husband loves their Coconut Thai curry and I love their horseradish crusted salmon. Their branzini, lamb loin, pork, and quail are all the total bomb. I pretty much live and die by their cheese cart, which I think is the absolute hands down the freakin BEST in the city. That rolling cart comes my way and I wanna shout at the top of my lungs, "Push that cheese into my face! :-)" Seriously, folks, for all you cheese lovers out there, get thee to your awaiting mecca. These people take their cheese seriously. I'm so over people taking cheese straight out of the refrigerator, and hurling a soft ripened brillat savarin or epoisse or brie at me. Is it a hockey puck or meant to be oozing butter like onto bread? The restaurant inevitably gives me a song and dance about some "city health ordinance" requiring them to refrigerate their cheese. I'd go to Gary Danko for their cheese course alone, an unforgettable experience and education in its own right. The variety of cheese is ridiculous--sheep, goat, cow . . . it's all there. Soft and creamy to hard--young and fresh to aged years. Tell them what you like and don't, they customize everything, and here's the best part: they engage in conversation with you about this process, e.g. I told them I need to avoid everything aged beyond 9 months (due to allergy), which they carefully selected out of. The desserts, my gosh it's a paradise for my husband with the sweet tooth that doesn't not quit. You souffle lovers out there, make a run for G.D.--each souffle is divine. As if the desset isn't enough, they'll close out the dinner with a little tray of sweet bites: mignardises. And as we're waddling out he door, they press a beautifully wrapped in gold paper gift into our hands; it's been a mini muffin or fresh bread or more sweets :-) The customer service is one of the best in the world. They actually give a damn, and want to please you, want to make you happy. This is not just a "job" for them. It's a career, which they take pride in, and clearly went to a hell of a training for. It's like stepping into a time warp of yesteryear--the service is everything: genteel, old world, courtly, kind and caring; every single person from start to finish, from being greeted to bidding farewell, they are individually and collectively masterful at makes us feel cared for. I wouldn't be surprised if they went to four years of hospitality school :-) Yes, G.D. cooks and serve superlative food but this is secondary to their main job: they make us feel loved.

    After a full day of early drinking and "running" for Bay to Breakers 2012, the only obvious choice for dinner before my flight home was to eat at Gary Danko. It was already a day of excess so why not add more excess, in the form or foie gras, to dinner as well.

    Did not have reservation but arrived shortly after they opened to grab at seat at the bar. In a way, bar seating is actually better because unlike the regular tables, you aren't forced to choose a 3-4-5 course meal, you can go a la carte. I went for the 3 course and each was just as heavenly as the next.

    Started off with an amuse of carrot soup. I never really liked cooked carrots but the flavors in this soup was so much more.

    First course was the foie gras. It was sitting on a bed of caramelized onions, I think. With a small mache salad on the side. Melt in my mouth goodness! This was no small piece that left you wanting more, I think it was the size of a small steak! I'm glad I was able to stuff myself with such a delicious and large amount of foie before the stupid ban takes place.

    Second got the branzini. The crust was super crispy without the rest of the fish being too dry either. It was sitting on a puree, which I can't remember what it was. Although it was good, this was probably my least favorite dish of the three I got. Nothing against it, but I'm just partial to my fobby style steamed fish. You can take the girl out of China, but not the China out of the girl I guess.

    Last course for me was the duck breast on duck confit hash. Let's talk about this hash first. It was more like a ball of crispy duck confit with a speckle of potatoes in it, that's how generous they are with the duck in this hash. The duck breast was medium and tender and perfect compliment to eat with the hash. This dish was just as generous in their portions too! I've been to Michelin star places leaving hungry after a 5 course meal, but halfway through the duck all the rich food was settling in. This is a place where you get both quality and quantity.

    My friends ordered dessert so I got to try both the Chocolate souffle and the butter cake. The souffle was light as air, but I felt like it needed to be drenched with more chocolate, it's just my preference for anything chocolate to be thick rich and decadent. The butter cake was all that and more. One bite and you can taste the butter, apple, spices all melt and meld in your mouth. Top that with the vanilla ice cream on the side and it was a perfect end to the meal. I wish I lived closer because I would definitely come back, four courses next time! =)

    3/26/2014

    Californian cusine in SF is definitely a game that you're a part of whether you knew it or not.  The players are the range of restaurants who invite you to sit and experience how they each choose to play the game.  If in the end you find yourself a used and abused fan, they ask you to not hate the player but yes, hate the game.

    On the surface, Californian cuisine is all about fusion. Echoing the state's progressive public policies, it means integrating disparate elements and techniques to harness the best each has to offer.  This results in a compelling platform or presentation and wow, are Californian cusine dishes compelling.  Pretty, so pretty.  But drilling down on these tanatlizing presentations, you'll find that while the common accenting of dishes with avocado, figs, persimmons and such provide for an air of healthy freshness, the game is played at a much deeper level.  Like in politics, it's ultimately all about the rich, and Californian cuisine is deceptively rich.  For example, don't be surprised if there's a full cup of creme (fresh, of course, however) in that small bowl of butternut squash soup.  So when they're wheeling your ass out in a butter coma whith a smile on your face, you'll at least know why.

    These are the masters of the game.  I enjoy being duped by these all-stars every time and I think you will, too.

    I was so ready to bring the hate for this place but they totally won me over.  One of the premiere SF restaurants that actually push beyond my cynical appraisal of the genre.  Everything was 5 stars: food, service, and ambience.
